observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management observe the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to have reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability as follows:

Follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, Recognition of PPE items found at station and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, and require the Municipal Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the actual physical inventory and effect necessary adjustments;

Adopt the uniform numbering system for property numbers of PPE and require the Property Unit to update the property stickers based on the prescribed format and to include the required information under Section 5.6 and 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team within the prescribed period;

Conduct the required preliminary activities prior to inventory taking; and

Record / document the physical count daily in a standard ICF prescribed in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended the following:
That the Municipal Accountant shall book up as Expenses all obligations incurred during the year as required in Section 119 of PD 1445and Section 7 of IPSAS 1;
At the end of the year and in cases where payment cannot be effected yet, said obligations shall be booked up as Expense and corresponding Accounts Payable set-up;
That the Municipal Budget Officer shall adopt appropriate measures to control the charges, made under the appropriations of programs, projects and activities to which it was created and to ensure that all obligations are duly backed up with, not only the availability of appropriations, but the cash availability as well.

